lines.value: washington is a state in the pacific northwest of the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the state is named after george washington the first president of the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: as of the 2000 census the state population was approximately 5.9 million and the state work force numbered about 3.1 million
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: residents are called washingtonians emphasis on the third syllable pronounced as tone
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it should not be confused with washington dc the nation's capital city
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: to avoid confusion the city is often called simply dc and the state is often called washington state
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington is bounded by the pacific ocean to the west oregon to the south the columbia river forming most of this border idaho to the east and british columbia canada to the north
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it is famous for scenery of breathtaking beauty and sharp contrasts
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: high mountains rise above evergreen forests and sparkling coastal waters
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: its coastal location and puget sound harbors give it a leading role in trade with alaska canada and the pacific rim
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: puget sound's many islands are served by the largest ferry fleet in the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington is a land of contrasts
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the deep forests of the olympic peninsula are among the rainiest places in the world and the only rainforests such as the hoh rain forest in the continental united states but the flat semi desert that lies east of the cascade range stretches for long distances without a single tree
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: snow covered peaks tower above the foothills and lowlands around them
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: mount rainier the highest mountain in the state appears to float on the horizon southeast of seattle and tacoma on clear days
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the eastern side of the state can be divided into two regions the okanogan highlands and the columbia river basin
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: areas under the management of the national park service include
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: prior to the arrival of explorers from europe this region of the pacific coast had many established tribes of native americans each with its own unique culture
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: today they are most notable for their totem poles and their ornately carved canoes and masks
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: prominent among their industries were salmon fishing and whale hunting
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in the east nomadic tribes traveled the land and missionaries such as the whitmans settled there
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the first european record of a landing on the washington coast was by spanish captain don bruno de heceta in 1775 on board the santiago part of a two ship flotilla with the sonora
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they claimed all the coastal lands up to the russian possessions in the north for spain
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 1778 british explorer captain james cook sighted cape flattery at the entrance to the strait of juan de fuca but the straits would not be explored until 1789 by captain charles w barkley
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: further explorations of the straits were performed by spanish explorers manuel quimper in 1790 and francisco de eliza in 1791 then by british captain george vancouver in 1792
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the spanish nootka convention of 1790 opened the northwest territory to explorers and trappers from other nations most notably britain and then the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: captain robert gray for whom grays harbor county is named then discovered the mouth of the columbia river
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: he named the river after his ship the columbia
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: beginning in 1792 gray established trade in sea otter pelts
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the lewis and clark expedition entered the state on october 10 1805
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 1819 spain ceded their original claims to this territory to the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this began a period of disputed joint occupancy by britain and the us that lasted until june 15 1846 when britain ceded their claims to this land with the treaty of oregon
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: because of the overland migration along the oregon trail many settlers wandered north to what is now washington and settled the puget sound area
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the first settlement was new market now known as tumwater in 1846
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 1853 washington territory was formed from part of oregon territory
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington became the 42 nd state in the united states on november 11 1889
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: early prominent industries in the state included agriculture and lumber
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in eastern washington the yakima valley became known for its apple orchards while the growth of wheat using dry farming techniques became particularly productive
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the heavy rainfall to the west of the cascade range produced dense forests and the ports along puget sound prospered from the manufacturing and shipping of lumber products particularly the douglas fir
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: other industries that developed in the state include fishing salmon canning and mining
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: by the turn of the 20th century washington was of dangerous repute in the minds of many americans
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: indisputably as wild as the rest of the american old west the public image of washington merely replaced cowboys with lumberjacks and desert with forestland
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: one city in particular aberdeen had the distinction of being the roughest town west of the mississippi because of excessive gambling violence extreme drug use and prostitution the city itself changed very little over the years and remained off limits to military personnel well into the early 1980s
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: for a long period tacoma was noted for its large smelters where gold silver copper and lead ores were treated
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: seattle was the primary port for trade with alaska and the rest of the country and for a time it possessed a large ship building industry
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the region around eastern puget sound developed heavy industry during the period including world war i and world war ii and the boeing company became an established icon in the area
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during the great depression a series of hydroelectric dams were constructed along the columbia river as part of a project to increase the production of electricity
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this culminated in 1941 with the completion of the grand coulee dam the largest dam in the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during world war ii the puget sound area became a focus for war industries with the boeing company producing many of the nation's heavy bombers and ports in seattle bremerton and tacoma were available for the manufacture of warships
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: seattle was the point of departure for many soldiers in the pacific a number of which were quartered at golden gardens park
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in eastern washington the hanford works atomic energy plant was opened in 1943 and played a major role in the construction of the nation's atomic bombs
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on may 18 1980 following a period of heavy tremors and eruptions the northeast face of mount st helens exploded outward destroying a large part of the top of the volcano
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this eruption flattened the forests killed 57 people flooded the columbia river and its tributaries with ash and mud and blanketed large parts of washington in ash making day look like night
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the racial ethnic makeup of the state there are many migrant mexican farm workers living in the southeast central part of the state
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: wahkiakum county as well as most counties in the state has many residents of scandinavian origin
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington has the fifth largest asian population of any state with chinese and fillipino being the largest groups
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: 6.7% of washington's population was reported as under 5 25.7% under 18 and 11.2% were 65 or older
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: females made up approximately 50.2% of the population
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the religious affiliations of washington's population are
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the 2004 total gross state product for washington was $262 billion placing it 14th in the nation
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the per capita income was $33332
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: significant business within the state include the design and manufacture of jet aircraft boeing computer software development microsoft amazon.com nintendo of america electronics biotechnology aluminum production lumber and wood products mining and tourism
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the state has significant amounts of hydroelectric power generation
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: significant amounts of trade with asia pass through the ports of the puget sound
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: see list of united states companies by state
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the state of washington is one of only seven states that does not levy a personal income tax
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: neither does the state collect a corporate income tax
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however washington businesses are responsible for various other state levies
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington's state sales tax is 7.9 percent and it applies to services as well as products
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: most foods are exempt from sales tax however prepared foods dietary supplements and soft drinks remain taxable
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the combined state and local retail sales tax rates increase the taxes paid by consumers depending on the variable local sales tax rates generally between 8 and 9 percent
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: an excise tax applies to certain select products such as gasoline cigarettes and alcoholic beverages
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: property tax was the first tax levied in the state of washington and its collection accounts for about 30 percent of washington's total state and local revenue
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it continues to be the most important revenue source for public schools fire protection library park and recreation and other special purpose districts
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: all real and personal property is subject to tax unless specifically exempted by law
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: personal property also is taxed although most personal property owned by individuals is exempt
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: personal property tax applies to personal property used when conducting business or to other personal property not exempt by law
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: all property taxes are paid to the county treasurer's office where the property is located
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington does not impose a tax on intangible assets such as bank accounts stocks or bonds
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: neither does the state assess any tax on retirement income earned and received from another state
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington does not collect inheritance taxes however the estate tax is decoupled from the federal estate tax laws and therefore the state imposes its own estate tax
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: thumbnail|right|125px|a [[whitman county washington|whitman county farm]] washington is a leading agricultural state
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the following figures are from the washington state office of financial management and the washington agricultural statistics service for 2003 the total value of washington's agricultural products was $5.79 billion the 11th highest in the country
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the total value of its crops was $3.8 billion the 7th highest
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the total value of its livestock and specialty products was $1.5 billion the 26th highest
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 2004 washington ranked first in the nation in production of red raspberries 90.0% of total us production wrinkled seed peas 80.6% hops 75.0% spearmint oil 73.6% apples 58.1% sweet cherries 47.3% pears 42.6% peppermint oil 40.3% concord grapes 39.3% carrots for processing 36.8% and niagara grapes 31.6%
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington also ranked second in the nation in production of lentils fall potatoes dry edible peas apricots grapes all varieties taken together asparagus over a third of the nation's production sweet corn for processing and green peas for processing third in tart cherries prunes and plums and dry summer onions fourth in barley and trout and fifth in wheat cranberries and strawberries
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington has an extensive system of state highways called state routes as well as the third largest ferry system in the world
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: there are 140 public airfields in washington including 16 state airports owned by the washington state department of transportation
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: boeing field in seattle is the busiest airport by numbers of planes in the world
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the unique geography of washington presents exceptional transportation needs
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: there are extensive waterways in the midst of washington's largest cites including seattle bellevue tacoma and olympia
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the state highways incorporate an extensive network of bridges and the largest ferry system in the united states to serve transpiration needs in the puget sound area
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington's marine highway constitutes a fleet of twenty eight ferries that navigate puget sound and its inland waterways to 20 different ports of call
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington is home for the five longest floating bridges in the world the evergreen point floating bridge lacey v murrow memorial bridge and homer m hadley bridge over lake washington and the hood canal bridge connecting the olympic and kitsap peninsulas
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the cascade mountain range also provides unique transportation challenges
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington operates and maintains 7 major mountain passes and 8 minor passes
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during winter months these passes are plowed sanded and kept safe with avalanche control
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: not all are able to stay open through the winter
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the north cascades highway on state route 20 closes every year
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: because of the extraordinary amount of snowfall and frequency of avalanches the highway is not safe in the winter months
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington has 49 legislative districts and elects one senator and two house members from each district
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the majority party is the democratic party
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington state senators and representatives are elected for four year and two year terms respectively
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: there are no term limits
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington's executive branch is headed by a governor elected for a four year term
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the current governor of washington is christine gregoire a democrat
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: she has been governor since 2005
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the washington supreme court is the highest court in the judiciary of the state of washington
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: nine justices serve on the bench and are elected at large
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the two us senators from washington are senator patty murray d and senator maria cantwell d
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington representatives in the united states house of representatives are jay inslee d-1 richard ray rick larsen d-2 brian baird d-3 richard norman doc hastings r-4 cathy mcmorris r-5 norm dicks d-6 jim mcdermott d-7 david reichert r-8 and adam smith d-9
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: * washington supreme court
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the state has been thought of as politically divided by the cascade mountains with western washington being liberal particularly greater seattle and eastern washington being conservative
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: since the population is larger in the west the democrats usually fare better statewide
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington has voted for the democratic candidate in presidential elections recently in 1988 1992 1996 2000 and 2004
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it was considered a key swing state in 1968 and 2000
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 1968 it was the only western state to give its electoral votes to hubert humphrey
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while the democratic party has long dominated washington the 2004 washington gubernatorial election was among the closest races in united states election history
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the initial count as well as the first recount conducted by machine both showed dino rossi the republican candidate winning the election
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a second recount was done by hand overturning the initial results when it resulted in a lead for christine gregoire the democratic candidate of 129 votes or 0.0045% of those cast
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: as this second recount was the last allowed for by washington election law gregoire was inaugurated on 12 january 2005
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the subsequent court battles raged for months after the election but ultimately ended with gregoire retaining her office
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the final official count left gregoire ahead by 133 votes
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: washington has the distinction for being the first and so far only state to elect women to all three major statewide offices state governor and two us senate seats at the same time
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on january 30 2006 governor christine gregoire signed into law legislation making washington the 17th state in the nation to protect gay and lesbian people from discrimination in housing lending and employment and the 7th state in the nation to offer these protections to transgendered people
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: initiative activist tim eyman filed a referendum that same day seeking to put the issue before the state's voters
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: despite a push from conservative churches across the state to gather signatures on what were dubbed referendum sundays eyman was only able to gather 105103 signatures more than 7000 signatures short of the minimum
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: as a result the law went into effect on june 7 2006
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cypyan mnnnnn mekcnka ncnahnenn himno nacional mexicano pacmah conn 1943 kabyn wyaaact
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 1854 jaime nuno arranged the music which now accompanies gonzalez's poem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the anthem consisting of ten stanzas and a chorus entered into use on september 16 1854
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: from 1854 until its official adoption the lyrics underwent several modifications due to political changes in mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: unofficially the anthem is sometimes called mexicanos al grito de guerra ncnahnenn for mexicans at the cry of war and is also the first line of the chorus
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on november 12 1853 president antonio lopez de santa anna announced a competition to write a national anthem for mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the competition offered a prize for the best poetic composition representing patriotic ideals
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: francisco gonzalez bocanegra a talented poet was not interested in participating in the competition
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: he argued that writing love poems involved very different skills from the ones required to write a national anthem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: his fiancee guadalupe gonzalez del pino or pili had undaunted faith in her fiance's poetic skills and was displeased with his constant refusal to participate in spite of her constant prodding and requests from their friends
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: finally she decided to take matters into her own hands
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: under false pretenses she lured him to a secluded bedroom in her parents house locked him into the room and refused to let him out until he produced an entry for the competition
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: inside the room in which he was temporarily imprisoned were pictures depicting various events in mexican history which helped to inspire his work
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: after four hours of fluent albeit forced inspiration francisco regained his freedom by slipping all ten verses of his creation under the door
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: after francisco received approval from his fiancee and her father he submitted the poem and won the competition by unanimous vote
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: gonzalez was announced the winner in the publication official journal of the federation dof on february 3 1854
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: at the same time the lyrics were chosen a set of music was chosen
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the winner was juan bottesini but his entry was disliked due to aesthetics
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this rejection caused a second national contest to find music for the lyrics
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: at the end of the second contest the music that was chosen for gonzalez's lyrics was composed by jaime nuno a spanish born band leader
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: at the time of the second anthem competition nuno was the leader of several mexican military bands
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: he had been invited to direct these bands by president santa anna whom he had met in cuba
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: about the time that nuno first came to mexico to start performing with the bands santa anna was making his announcement about creating a national anthem for mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: out of the few musical compositions submitted nuno's music titled god and freedom dios y libertad was chosen as the winner on august 12 1854
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the anthem was officially adopted on independence day september 16 of that same year
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the inaugural interpretation was directed by juan bottesini sung by soprano claudia florenti and tenor lorenzo salvi at the santa anna theatre now known as the national theatre of mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: officially since 1943 the full national anthem consists of the chorus 1st stanza 5th stanza 6th stanza and 10th stanza
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the modification of the lyrics was ordered by president manuel avila camacho in a decree printed in the diario oficial de la federacion
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: when mexican anthem is played at sporting events such as the olympic games the only parts of the anthem that are played are the chorus 1st stanza and the chorus
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: when opening and closing television and or radio programming stations have sometimes played a modified national anthem consisting of the chorus 1st stanza chorus 10th stanza and chorus
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: notes the official lyrics are in spanish but as of december 9 2005 the mexican government has allowed for various native peoples of mexico to translate the lyrics into their native languages
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the translation will be performed by the national institute of indigenous languages instituto nacional de lenguas indigenas
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the word patria in the spanish language is the feminine form of the english term for the homeland motherland/fatherland
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: national anthem of mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: an urban legend about the copyright status of the mexican anthem states that years after the first performance of the anthem nuno's family sold the anthem's musical rights to a german music publishing company named wagner house
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: originally nuno was supposed to have turned the music rights over to the state in exchange for a prize from the mexican government
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however according to the myth the copyright changed hands again this time to nuno himself and two americans harry henneman and phil hill
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in reality however this is not entirely correct
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it is true that nuno henneman and hill did register the music with the company bmi bmi work 568879 with the edward b marks music company as the listed publisher of the anthem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this might be the version that some have suggested is copyrighted in the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however united states copyright law declares the mexican anthem to be in the public domain inside the united states since both the lyrics and music were published before 1909
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: furthermore under mexican copyright law article 155 states that the government holds moral rights but not property rights of the national symbols including the anthem coat of arms and the national flag
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in the second chapter of the law regarding the national arms flag and anthem ley sobre el escudo la bandera y el himno nacionales mexico's national anthem is described in very brief terms
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while articles 2 and 3 discuss in detail the coat of arms and the flag respectively article 4 mentions only that the national anthem will be designated by law
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 4 also mentions that a copy of the lyrics and the musical notation will be kept at two locations the general national archive and at the national library located in the national museum of history biblioteca nacional en el museo nacional de historia
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: chapter 5 of the law goes into more detail about how to honor respect and properly perform the national anthem article 38 states that the singing playing reproduction and circulation of the national anthem are regulated by law and that any interpretation of the anthem must be performed in a respectful way and in a scope that allows [one] to observe the due solemnity of the anthem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 39 prohibits the anthem from being altered in any fashion prohibits it from being sung for commercial or promotional purposes and also disallows the singing or playing of national anthems from other nations unless you have permission from the secretary of the interior secretaria de gobernacion and the diplomatic official from the nation in question
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the secretary of the interior and the secretary of public education secretaria de educacion publica in article 40 must grant permission for all reproductions of the national anthem to be produced unless the anthem is being played during official ceremonies carried on the radio or television
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 41 states that the national anthem is required to be played at the beginning or end of radio and television programing
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the extra requirement for television programing is that photos of the mexican flag must be displayed at the same time the anthem is playing
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 42 states that the anthem may only be used during the following occasions solemn acts of official civic cultural scholastic or sport character
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the anthem can also be played to render honors to the mexican flag and to the president of mexico
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: if the national anthem is being used to honor the national flag or the president the short version of the anthem is played
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 43 says that special musical honors may be paid to the president and the flag but no more than once during the same ceremony
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 44 says that during solemn occasions if a choir is singing the anthem the military bands will keep silent
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 45 says that those who are watching the national anthem performance must stand at attention firmes and remove any headgear
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 46 states that the national anthem must be taught to children who are attending primary or secondary school this article was amended in 2005 to add pre school to the list
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the article also states that each school in the national education system sistema educativo nacional will be asked to sing the national anthem each year
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 47 states that during an official welcoming ceremony for a head of state the guest's anthem will be played first then the mexican anthem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: article 48 states that at embassies and consulates of mexico the national anthem is played at ceremonies of a solemn nature that involves the mexican people
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: if the anthem is played outside of mexico article 48 requires that the secretary of external relations secretaria de relaciones exteriores through proper channels must grant permission for the national anthem to be played and will also ensure that the anthem is not sung for commercial purposes
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: upon the writing of the anthem mexico was still facing the effects of a defeat in a war with the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the country felt demoralized and also divided due to the loss of more than half of the territory to the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: according to historian javier garciadiego who spoke at a ceremony commemorating the 150th anniversary of the anthem's adoption said that the anthem disregards divisions and strife and encourages national unity
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: also during the celebration in 2004 mexico city and other parts of the country stopped what they were doing and performed a nationwide singing of the anthem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: individuals from other nations participated mostly at diplomatic offices or at locations where a high concentration of mexican expatriates are found
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the anthem has also been described as one of the symbols of the mexican identity in the rare occasions when someone performs the anthem incorrectly the federal government has been known to impose penalties to maintain the dignity of the national symbols
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: one example is when a performer forgot some of the lyrics at a soccer match in guadalajara she was fined 40 usd by the interior ministry and released an apology letter to the country through the interior ministry
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in addition the anthem is sometimes used as a tool against people who might not be true mexicans
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in one case minority groups such as the black mexicans have been stopped by police and forced to sing the anthem to prove their nationality
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in a separate incident in japan police officers asked four men to sing the mexican anthem after they were arrested in tokyo on charges of breaking and entering
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however when the men could not sing the anthem it was discovered that they were colombian nationals holding forged mexican passports
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they were later charged with more counts on theft of merchandise and money
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while the official language of mexico is spanish there are still people who only speak traditional languages
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on december 8 of 2005 article 39 of the national symbols law was adopted to allow for the translation of the lyrics into the native languages
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the official translation is performed by the national institute of indigenous languages instituto nacional de lenguas indigenas
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: . officially the national anthem has been translated into the following native languages chinanteco hna hnu mixteco maya nahuatl and tenek
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: other native groups have translated the anthem into their respective language but it has not been sanctioned by the government
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: se conmueven del inca las tumbas y en sus huesos revive el ardor lo que va renovando a sus hijos de la patria el antiguo esplendor
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: pero sierras y muros se sienten retumbar con horrible fragor todo el pais se conturba por gritos de venganza de guerra y furor
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: en los fieros tiranos la envidia escupio su pestifera hiel su estandarte sangriento levantan provocando a la lid mas cruel
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: ?no los veis sobre mexico y quito arrojarse con sana tenaz y cual lloran banados en sangre potosi cochabamba y la paz
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: ?no los veis sobre el triste caracas luto y llantos y muerte esparcir
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: ?no los veis devorando cual fieras todo pueblo que logran rendir
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a vosotros se atreve argentinos el orgullo del vil invasor vuestros campos ya pisa contando tantas glorias hollar vencedor
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: mas los bravos que unidos juraron su feliz libertad sostener a estos tigres sedientos de sangre fuertes pechos sabran oponer
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: el valiente argentino a las armas corre ardiendo con brio y valor el clarin de la guerra cual trueno en los campos del sud resono
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: buenos ayres se opone a la frente de los pueblos de la inclita union y con brazos robustos desgarran al iberico altivo leon
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: san jose san lorenzo suipacha ambas piedras salta y tucuman la colonia y las mismas murallas del tirano en la banda oriental
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: son letreros eternos que dicen aqui el brazo argentino triunfo aqui el fiero opresor de la patria su cerviz orgullosa doblo
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: la victoria al guerrero argentino con sus alas brillante cubrio y azorado a su vista el tirano con infamia a la fuga se dio
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: sus banderas sus armas se rinden por trofeos a la libertad y sobre alas de gloria alza el pueblo trono digno a su gran majestad
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: desde un polo hasta el otro resuena de la fama el sonoro clarin y de america el nombre ensenando les repite !mortales oid ya su trono dignisimo abrieron las provincias unidas del sud
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: y los libres del mundo responden al gran pueblo argentino !salud!sean eternos los laureles que supimos conseguir
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: coronados de gloria vivamos !o juremos con gloria morir
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: successful cultivation of cotton requires a long growing season plenty of sunshine and water during the period of growth and dry weather for harvest

lines.value: in general these conditions are met within tropical and warm subtropical latitudes in the northern and southern hemispheres
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: production of the crop for a given year usually starts soon after harvesting the preceding autumn
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: planting time in spring varies from the beginning of february to the beginning of june

lines.value: ecotton fiber originates from the cotton plant an important crop in tropical climates and warm temperate climates

lines.value: commercial species of cotton plant are gossypium hirsutum usa and australia g

lines.value: cotton has been used to make very fine lightweight nnboc in areas with tropical climates for millennia
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: some authorities claim that it was likely that the mncpians had cotton as early as 12000 bc and evidence has been found of cotton in mekcnkon caves cotton cloth and fragments of bloody fibre interwoven with naps and nap which dated back to approximately 7000 years ago
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: there is clear archaeological evidence that people in south america and india domesticated different species of cotton independently thousands of years ago
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the earliest reference to cotton is in xnhayctoh
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton has been grown in india/pakistan for more than 6000 years since the pre harappan period and it is later referred to in the rig veda composed in 3000 bc two thousand years later the famous greek historian herodotus wrote about indian cotton there are trees which grow wild there the fruit of which is a wool exceeding in beauty and goodness that of sheep
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the indians make their clothes of this tree wool
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: book iii
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: 106)in nepy cotton was the backbone of the development of coastal cultures such as the moche and nazca
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton was grown upriver made into nets and traded with fishing villages along the coast for large supplies of fish
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the spanish who came to mexico in the early 1500s found the peoples there wearing cotton clothing and growing it.during the late mediaeval period cotton became known as an imported fibre in northern europe without any knowledge of what it came from other than that it was a plant people in the region familiar only with animal fibres wool from sheep could only imagine that cotton must be produced by plant borne sheep
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: john mandeville writing in 1350 stated as fact the now preposterous belief there grew there india a wonderful tree which bore tiny lambs on the endes of its branches
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: these branches were so pliable that they bent down to allow the lambs to feed when they are hungrie
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this aspect is retained in the name for cotton in many european languages such as german baumwolle which translates as tree wool
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: by the end of the 16th century ad cotton was cultivated throughout the warmer regions in africa ebpaзnr and the amepnka
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the indian cotton processing industry was eclipsed during the british colonial rule as part of the british mercantile policy of deliberate and systematic de industrialization of india which forced the closing of indian factories and processing facilities
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the intent of this british policy was to ensure that colonized lands supplied raw materials and that britain should retain a monopoly on manufacturing
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in addition the invention of the spinning jenny 1764 and arkwright's spinning frame 1769 enabled cheap mass production of cotton cloth in the uk
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: production capacity was further improved by the invention of the cotton gin by eli whitney in 1793
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: as a result of these policies and developments british traders developed a commercial chain in which raw cotton fibres were sourced initially from their colonies processed into cotton cloth in the mills of lancashire and then reexported back on british ships to their captive colonial markets in west africa india and china via colonized shanghai and hong kong
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: later when the superiority of the american varieties of cotton was established owing primarily to the length of the fibers the british started purchasing cotton from slave plantations in the united states and the caribbean
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: due to the enormous quantities of raw cotton required to make cheap bulk exports british industrialists quickly abandoned expensive raw cotton produced in india in favour of mass produced cotton from the southern united states which was much cheaper as it was produced by unpaid slaves
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: by the mid nineteenth century king cotton had become the backbone of the southern american economy and today roughly 90% of the world's cotton crop is of the long staple american variety
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in the united states growing the three crops cotton indigo and tamoky historically was the leading occupation of fynomoh
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: after emancipation the share cropping system evolved which in many cases differed little from the systems of slavery
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during the american civil war american cotton exports slumped due to a union blockade on southern ports prompting the main purchasers of cotton britain and france to turn to egyptian cotton
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: british and french traders invested heavily in egyptian cotton plantations and the egyptian government of viceroy isma'il took out substantial loans from european bankers and stock exchanges
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: after the american civil war ended in 1865 british and french traders abandoned egyptian cotton in favour of cheap exports from the united states sending egypt into a deficit spiral that led to the country declaring bankruptcy in 1876
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: today cotton is produced in many parts of the world including every continent except antarctica
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton plants have been selectively bred so that each plant grows more fiber
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in 2002 cotton was grown on 330000 km² of farmland
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: 47 billion pounds 21 million t of raw cotton worth 20 billion usd was grown that year
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the cotton industry relies heavily on chemicals such as fertilizers and insecticides although a very small number of farmers are moving towards an organic model of production and organic cotton products are now available for purchase at limited locations
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: historically in north america one of the most economically destructive pests in cotton production has been the boll weevil
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: due to the us department of agriculture's highly successful boll weevil eradication program bwep this pest has been eliminated from cotton in most of the united states
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this program along with the introduction of genetically engineered cotton containing a gene that codes for a plant produced protein that is toxic to a number of pests such as tobacco budworm cotton bollworm and pink bollworm has allowed a reduction in the use of synthetic insecticides
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: most cotton in the united states europe and australia is harvested mechanically either by a cotton picker a machine that removes the cotton from the boll without damaging the cotton plant or by a cotton stripper which strips the entire boll off the plant
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton strippers are generally used in regions where it is too windy to grow picker varieties of cotton and generally used after application of a defoliant or natural defoliation occurring after a freeze
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton is a perennial crop in the tropics and without defoliation or freezing the plant will continue to grow
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the logistics of cotton harvesting and processing have been improved by the development of the cotton module builder a machine that compresses harvested cotton into a large block which is then covered with a tarp and temporarily stored at the edge of the field
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: beginning as a self help program in the mid 1960s the cotton research & promotion program was organized by us upland cotton producers in response to cotton's steady decline in market share
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: at that time producers voted to set up a per bale assessment system to fund the program with built in safeguards to protect their investments
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: with the passage of the cotton research & promotion act of 1966 the program joined forces and began battling synthetic competitors and reestablishing markets for cotton
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: today the success of this program has made cotton the best selling fiber in the us and one of the best selling fibers in the world
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: administered by the cotton board and conducted by cotton incorporated the cotton research & promotion program is the program that is continuously working to increase the demand for and profitability of cotton through various research and promotion activities
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the program is funded by us cotton producers and importers
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: egyptian cotton is considered to be one of the best types of cotton and is produced in various quality levels in long staple ls and extra long staple els
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton is used to make a number of textile products
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: these include terrycloth used to make highly absorbent bath towels and robes denim used to make blue jeans chambray popularly used in the manufacture of blue work shirts from which we get the term blue collar along with corduroy seersucker and cotton twill
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: socks underwear and most t shirts are made from cotton
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: bed sheets are also often made from cotton
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton is also used to make yarn used in crochet and knitting
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while many fabrics are made completely of cotton some materials blend cotton with synthetic fibers such as polyester or rayon
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in addition to the textile industry cotton is used in fishnets coffee filters tents and in bookbinding
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the first chinese paper was made of cotton fibre as is the modern us dollar bill and federal stationery
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: fire hoses were once made of cotton
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the cottonseed which remains after the cotton is ginned is used to produce cottonseed oil which after refining can be consumed by humans like any other vegetable oil
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the cottonseed meal that is left is generally fed to livestock
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in the past cotton seeds were used by women as an abortifacient
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the greatest ecological threat to cotton plants is the boll weevil
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during the late nineteenth century and early twentieth century boll weevil infestations caused significant damage to annual cotton crops in the southern united states resulting in frequent economic depressions in rural areas
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cotton is an enormously important commodity throughout the world
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however many farmers in developing countries receive a low price for their produce or find it difficult to compete with developed countries
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this has led to fair trade cotton clothing or footwear veja sneakers being available in some countries

lines.value: bamiyan lies on the silk road a caravan route linking the markets of china with those of south asia central asia middle east and europe
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it was the site of several buddhist monasteries and a thriving center for religion philosophy and greco buddhist art
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it was a buddhist religious site from the second century up to the time of the islamic invasion in the ninth century
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: monks at the monasteries lived as hermits in small caves carved into the side of the bamiyan cliffs
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: many of these monks embellished their caves with religious statuary and elaborate brightly colored frescoes
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the two most prominent statues were the giant standing buddhas measuring 55 and 37 meters 180 and 121 feet high respectively the largest examples of standing buddha carvings in the world
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they were perhaps the most famous cultural landmarks of the region and the site was listed by unesco as a world heritage site along with surrounding cultural landscape and archaeological remains of the bamiyan valley
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the smaller of the two statues about 120 feet tall was built in the 3rd century ad the larger one at 175 feet was constructed in the 5th century ad the statues are believed to have been built by the indo european kushans and hephthalites at the hey day of their empires
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: ironically the above mentioned tribes also formed the basis of pashtun ethnogenesis -  the ethnic group from which the taliban drew its core following
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: chinese buddhist pilgrim hsuan-tsang xuanzang passed through the area around 630 ad and described bamiyan as a flourishing buddhist centre with more than ten monasteries and more than a thousand monks and he noted that both buddha figures were decorated with gold and fine jewels wriggins 1995
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a monumental sitting buddha similar in style to those at bamiyan still exists in the bingling temple caves in china's gansu province
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: when mahmud of ghazni conquered afghanistan in the 12th century the buddhas and frescoes were spared from destruction
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: aurangzeb the last mughal emperor distinguished for his religious zeal employed heavy artillery in an attempt to destroy the statues
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: genghis khan and nadir shah too had cannon fire directed at the statues
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: but over the centuries the statues had largely been left untouched
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in july 1999 mullah mohammed omar issued a decree in favor of the preservation of the bamiyan buddhas
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: because afghanistan's buddhist population no longer existed which removed the possibility of the statues being worshiped he added the government considers the bamiyan statues as an example of a potential major source of income for afghanistan from international visitors
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the taliban states that bamiyan shall not be destroyed but protected afghan's islamist clerics would begin a campaign to crack down on un islamic segments of afghan society
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the taliban soon banned all forms of imagery music and sports including television in accordance with what they considered a strict interpretation of islamic law
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in march 2001 according to agence france presse in kabul the decree declared based on the verdict of the clergymen and the decision of the supreme court of the islamic emirate taliban all the statues around afghanistan must be destroyed
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: all the statues in the country should be destroyed because these statues have been used as idols and deities by the non believers before
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they are respected now and may be turned into idols in future too
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: only allah the almighty deserves to be worshiped not anyone or anything else information and culture minister qadratullah jamal told associated press of a decision by 400 religious clerics from across afghanistan declaring the buddhist statues against the tenets of islam
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they came out with a consensus that the statues were unislamic said jamal
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on march 6 the london times quoted mullah mohammed omar as stating muslims should be proud of smashing idols
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it has given praise to god that we have destroyed them he had clearly changed his position from being in favor of the statues to being against them
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during a march 13 interview for japan's mainichi shimbun foreign afghan minister wakil ahmad mutawakel stated that the destruction was anything but a retaliation against the international community for economic sanctions we are destroying the buddha statues in accordance with islamic law and it is purely a religious issue
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on march 18 the new york times reports that a taliban envoy said the islamic government made its decision in a rage after a foreign delegation offered money to preserve the ancient works while a million afghans faced starvation
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the new york times also added however that other reports have said the religious leaders were debating the move for months and ultimately decided that the statues were idolatrous and should be obliterated then taliban ambassador at large and current yale student sayed rahmatullah hashemi said that the destruction of the statues was carried out during the famine in afghanistan after a swedish government earmarked money to be provided to restore the statues and refused to allow it to be used to aid afghan children
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: hashimi is reported as saying when the afghani head council asked them to provide the money to feed the children instead of fixing the statues they refused and said no the money is just for the statues not for the children
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: herein they made the decision to destroy the statues"
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: on april 19th 2004 in an interview to a pakistani journalist mohammad shehzad mullah mohammad omar said the following i did not want to destroy the bamiyan buddha
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in fact some foreigners came to me and said they would like to conduct the repair work of the bamiyan buddha that had been slightly damaged due to rains
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this shocked me
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: i thought these callous people have no regard for thousands of living human beings - the afghans who are dying of hunger but they are so concerned about non living objects like the buddha
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this was extremely deplorable
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: that is why i ordered its destruction
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: had they come for humanitarian work i would have never ordered the buddhas destruction the islamist taliban government decreed that the statues which had survived intact for over 1500 years were idolatrous and unislamic
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: during the destruction taliban information minister qudratullah jamal lamented that this work of destruction is not as easy as people might think
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: you can't knock down the statues by shelling as both are carved into a cliff they are firmly attached to the mountain the two largest buddhas faced dynamite and tank barrages and were demolished after almost a month of intensive bombardment
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: according to unesco director general koichiro matsuura a meeting of ambassadors from the 54 member states of the organisation of the islamic conference oic was conducted
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: all oic states including pakistan saudi arabia and the united arab emirates three countries that officially recognised the taliban government joined the protest to spare the monuments cnn
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a statement issued by the ministry of religious affairs of taliban regime justified the destruction as being in accordance with islamic law afp news
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: saudi arabia and the united arab emirates would later condemn the destruction as savage a swiss documentary reported that locals claimed to have seen pakistani and saudi engineers on site to help with the destruction of the statues a pakistani charity al rasheed trust based in karachi had published a special calendar with photographs of the destructions to commemorate the destruction
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: though the figures of the two large buddhas are almost completely destroyed their outlines and some features are still recognizable within the recesses
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it is also still possible for visitors to explore the monks caves and the passages which connect them
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: as part of the international effort to rebuild afghanistan after the taliban war the government of japan and several other organizations among them the afghanistan institute in bubendorf switzerland it can be considered as the afghan national museum in exile during the taliban period along with the eth in zurich have committed themselves to rebuilding the two largest buddhas anastylosis is one technique being considered
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in may 2002 a mountainside sculpture of the buddha was carved out of a mountain in sri lanka
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it was designed to closely resemble one of the buddhas of bamiyan
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in december 2004 japanese researchers discovered that the wall paintings at bamiyan were actually painted between the 5th and the 9th centuries rather than the 6th to 8th centuries as previously believed
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the discovery was made by analysing radioactive isotopes contained in straw fibers found beneath the paintings
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: further discoveries are expected to be made after comparing the paintings dates and styles
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the afghan government has commissioned japanese artist hiro yamagata to recreate the bamiyan buddhas using fourteen laser systems to project the images of the buddhas onto the cliff where they once stood
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the laser systems will be solar powered and wind powered
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the project which will cost an estimated $9 million is currently pending unesco approval
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: if approved the project is estimated to be completed by 2007
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in september 2005 mawlawi mohammed islam mohammadi taliban governor of bamiyan province at the time of the destruction was elected to the afghan parliament
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: swiss filmmaker christian frei made a 95-minute documentary the giant buddhas released in march 2006 on the statues the international reactions to it and an overview of the controversy
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the movie makes the controversial claim quoting a local afghan that the destruction was ordered by osama bin laden and that initially mullah omar and the afghans in bamiyan had opposed the destruction [http://web.archive.org/20060619051046/timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1466974.cms
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: times of india mar 27 2006)]
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: in the summer of 2006 afghani officials are deciding the timetable for the reconstruction of the statues
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the mullahs in the province have stated that the destruction was an atrocity and the statues deserve restoration
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while they wait for the afghan government and international community to decide whether to rebuild them a $1.3 million unesco funded project is sorting out the chunks of clay and plaster - ranging from boulders weighing several tons to fragments the size of tennis balls - and sheltering them from the elements

lines.value: freedom from such restrictions is central to the concept with the opposite of free software being proprietary software a distinction unrelated to whether a fee is charged
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the usual way for software to be distributed as free software is for the software to be licensed to the recipient with a free software license or be in the public domain and the source code of the software to be made available for a compiled language
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: mabmyntapnhn baphomaxon ponroh linux openoffice.org mozilla thunderbird ba fanpaxo mebowaha
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: linux ba openoffice.org ba зabohn tounkn hnз mabuyaaha
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: to help distinguish libre freedom software from gratis zero price software richard stallman founder of the free software movement developed the following explanation free software is a matter of liberty not price
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: to understand the concept you should think of free as in free speech not as in free beer
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: more specifically free software means that computer users have the freedom to cooperate with whom they choose and to control the software they use
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the gnu manifesto contains language that gives evidence of stallman's initial confusion with the usage
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: most free software is distributed online without charge or off line at the marginal cost of distribution but this is not required and people may sell copies for any price
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: thus free software is entirely compatible with commercial software a prohibition on selling the software would be a restriction failing the free software definition
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the capitalized term open source is attached to a definition originally created in 1998 from debian's free software guidelines
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: while most open source software is also free software and vice versa this is not always the case
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the free bsd based operating systems such as freebsd openbsd and netbsd use a similar definition of free software but they differ in interpretation about copyleft
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: users of these systems often see copyleft as being over restrictive to the point of being an encroachment on their freedom
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: freeware is software made available free of charge but is generally proprietary as users do not necessarily have the freedom to use copy study modify or redistribute it
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: source code for freeware may or may not be published and permission to distribute modified versions may or may not be granted so freeware is gratis and not libre software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: fsf's official definition for free software was first published in january 1989
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: this was later reworded by bruce perens to make the debian free software guidelines dfsg
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: when open source initiative was founded its board used the dfsg but with the words free software replaced with open source software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: these three definitions from fsf debian and osi are the only generally accepted definitions associated with free software by whichever name one calls it
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a brief history of free software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: according to stallman and the fsf software licenses must have the following four freedoms to qualify as being free free software foundation and open source initiative both publish lists of licenses that they find to comply with their definition of free software and open source software respectively
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the lists are necessarily incomplete because a license need not be known by either organisation in order to provide these freedoms
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: apart from these two organisations the debian project is seen by some to provide useful advice on whether particular licenses comply with their debian free software guidelines
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: debian doesn't publish a list of approved licenses so its judgements have to be tracked by checking what software they have allowed into their archives
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however it is rare that a license is announced as being in compliance by fsf or osi and not the other the netscape public license used for early versions of mozilla being an exception so exact definitions of the terms have not become hot issues
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the terms libre software floss foss and oss/fs do not have formal meanings or defacto arbitrators
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: most free software uses a small set of licenses
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the most popular of these are the gnu general public license the gnu lesser general public license the bsd license the mozilla public license the mit license and the apache license
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: software that is not free software is known as proprietary software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it may come with some or none of the above freedoms and almost always comes with an eula which purports to use contract law to restrict users ability to run the software in certain ways
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the fsf and osi definitions both disregard price
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: cds containing free software such as gnu/linux distributions are commonly for sale
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: if the cd buyer retains the free software freedoms the purchased software is still free software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: freeware includes restrictions that conflict with the free software definition are considered proprietary since source code may be unavailable or redistributors may be prohibited charging fees
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: some people use libre to avoid the ambiguity of the word free
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however these terms are mostly used within the free software movement
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: variations on free software as defined by the fsf all free software licenses must grant people all the freedoms discussed above
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however unless the applications licenses are compatible combining programs by mixing source code or directly linking binaries is problematic because of license technicalities
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: programs indirectly connected together may avoid this problem
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the most accessible and comprehensive collections of free software are currently distributed as livedistros entire operating systems stored and made ready to boot on cds usb sticks dvds and other bootable media
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: by inserting a livedistro into a cd drive and booting the computer arrives to a desktop with hundreds of free software packages ready to run and use
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: some free software like openoffice.org work on the non free microsoft windows and non free unix platforms
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: non free software can work on free platforms although purists prefer using platforms composed entirely of free software such as gnu/linux
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: free software is generally available at little to no cost and can result in permanently lower costs compared to proprietary software evidence by free software becoming popular in third world countries
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: with free software businesses have the freedom to fit the software to their specific needs by changing the software themselves or by hiring programmers to modify it for them
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: with proprietary software they would be at the mercy of the company developing the software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: free software gives users the ability to cooperate with each other in enhancing and refining the programs they use
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: free software is a pure public good rather than a private good
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: companies that contribute to free software can increase commercial innovation amidst the void of patent cross licensing lawsuits
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: see mpeg2 patent holders free software was the material that provided the internet the world wide web and the infrastructure of dot com companies
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: there is debate over the security of free software in comparison to proprietary software with a major issue being security through obscurity
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a popular quantitative test in computer security is using relative counting of known unpatched security flaws
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: generally users of this method advise avoiding products which lack fixes for known security flaws at least until a fix is available
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: some claim that method counts more vulnerabilities for the free software since their source code is accessible and their community is more forthcoming about what problems exist
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the ability to view and modify the software provides a practical defence against spyware
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it is often wondered why individuals would make the effort to participate and contribute to free software as such contributions can be very costly in terms of effort or time
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: one of the reasons is that individuals can earn a living doing so
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the free software foundation maintains a service directory of people offering their free software services for hire
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: it shows free software developers offer their services ranging from $35/hour to $250/hour and some companies rates for support for standard products start at $12500
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: some individuals perceive that they can start their own business at a fraction of the cost of proprietary software if they have the skills and knowledge required for example many web hosting companies exclusively use free software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: however direct economic benefit is hardly the main reason for the willingness of a wide community of individuals to contribute to free software
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: the main reason is simple the contributor actually gets back much more than she gives away
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: contributor a may be proficient in producing program a and contributor b in producing program b conversely contributor c may have experience in testing and debugging programs but not in programming them from scratch
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: if they share their efforts freely c might debug programs a and b and thus the three contributors could have high quality programs a and b whereas in a non free scenario a and b would have a single buggy program each and c would have nothing at all
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: a and b could try to sell their programs to each other or to c they could hire c to debug them
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: c could use his salary as debugger to buy programs a and or b however although a non free scenario could benefit highly a or b whoever has the most direly needed program the most positive outcome for the three of them at the same time would be without doubt obtained in the free scenario
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: individuals within a team typically have a wide variety of motivations
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: often there are stances on the relationship between free software and the existing business models that allow vendor lock in
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they may also believe in inter market competition and that free software is a form of competition within capitalism
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: they may also perceive that copyright systems and other intellectual property regimes government enforced monopolies market restrictions
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: other motivations may consist of gift economics where status depends effectively on gifts from the contributor
lines.name: Tajik

lines.value: or more prosaically a contributor may just want to altruistically do what he perceives as a good deed in the spirit of volunteerism
lines.name: Tajik
